<p><span style=3D"font-weight: 400;">We would then need to calculate how mu=
ch of an addition of water is needed to hit the mash out temperature of 74=
=C2=B0C. We will also assume the mash has cooled a few degrees to 65=C2=B0C=
, our grain bill is 4kg and initial mash liquor is 10 litres. If we add rec=
ently boiled water that has cooled to 95=C2=B0C we will need to use the fol=
lowing equation =E2=80=93 Wa =3D (T2-T1)(0.41G + Wm) / (Tw =E2=80=93 T2) ac=
hieving the following</span></p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p><span style=3D"font-weight: 400;">(75 =E2=80=93 65) x (1.64 + 10) / (95 =
=E2=80=93 75) =3D 5.82 litres</span></p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p data-slot-rendered-content=3D"true"><span style=3D"font-weight: 400;">So=
 we would add 5.83 litres of 95=C2=B0C water to take the mash from 65=C2=B0=
C to 75=C2=B0C. </span></p>
